{| class="infobox" width=230 |- |{{center|'''Events of years in sports'''}} |- style="background-color:#f3f3f3" |''Other years'' |- | align="center" | [[1601 to 1700 in sports|1601 to 1700]] | [[1701 to 1725 in sports|1701 to 1725]] | '''[[1726 to 1730 in sports|1726 to 1730]]''' | [[1731 to 1735 in sports|1731 to 1735]] | [[1736 to 1740 in sports|1736 to 1740]] |}
Events in world sport through the years 1726 to 1730.
==[[Boxing]]== '''Events''' * 1726 — in several fights to 1730, [[Jack Broughton]] defeated unnamed opponents and won the admiration of [[James Figg]].<ref name="JB">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/broughton-jack.htm |title=Jack Broughton |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> * 23 May 1727 — Figg and Ned Sutton fought in a 1 hour exhibition bout in London.<ref name="JF"/> * 30 May 1727 — Figg and Sutton fought in a second 1 hour exhibition bout in London.<ref name="JF"/> * 6 June 1727 — Figg defeated Sutton in a rematch for the English bare-knuckle boxing championship. The bout lasted ten minutes over eight rounds. Figg retained the title until his retirement in 1730.<ref name="JF">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/figg-james.htm |title=James Figg |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> * 1729 — Tom Pipes, one of Figg's students, claimed the vacant Championship of England title and was generally recognized as such. He had seven fights to 1733 against Bill Gretting, winning four and losing three, but it is unclear if any of them were championship bouts.<ref name="CBZ">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/barenuk.htm |title=The Bare Knuckle Heavyweight Champions of England |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref><ref name="TP">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/pipes-tom.htm |title=Tom Pipes |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> * 1730 — George Taylor began boxing at Figg's Amphitheatre and was a big favorite there.<ref name="GT">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/taylor-george.htm |title=George Taylor |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref>
==[[Cricket]]== [[Image:Oldest cricket bat.JPG|250px|thumb|right|The oldest surviving bat from 1729. Note its "hockey stick" shape, which is very different from modern-day bats.]] '''Events''' * 1727 — [[Charles Lennox, 2nd Duke of Richmond]] was involved in the creation of [[Articles of Agreement (cricket)|Articles of Agreement]] to establish the rules under which two matches were played, the first time that a set of rules is known to have been put in writing.<ref name=TJM>McCann, pp. 6–7.</ref> * 1728 — the earliest known instance of a county team (i.e., Kent) being acclaimed for its superiority over its rivals suggests the origin of the unofficial [[Champion County]] title.<ref>Waghorn, p. 7.</ref> * 1729 — the earliest known innings victory was achieved and 1729 is the date of the oldest known cricket bat still in existence.<ref>Bowen, p. 263.</ref>
